text.section:
Notwithstanding the provisions of subsections (b) and (c) of this section, if there are known or potential claims due the federal government, the following shall be the priority of distribution:
expenses of administration;
the following claims without priority among them:
claims made by policyholders, beneficiaries, insureds, or holders of funding agreements issued under § 16-113 of this article, that arise from and within the coverage of and are not in excess of the applicable limits of policies and insurance contracts issued by the insurer;
liability claims against insureds that are within the coverage of and are not in excess of the applicable limits of policies and insurance contracts issued by the insurer; and
claims of:
claims of the federal government not included in item (2) of this subsection;
the first $500 of compensation or wages owed to an officer or employee of an insurer for services rendered within 3 months before the commencement of a delinquency proceeding against the insurer, which shall be instead of any other similar priority that may be authorized by law as to wages or compensation;
claims for taxes and debts due any state or local government; and
all other claims of general creditors not falling within any other priority under this subsection.
